f   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Mormaer was born in 1173, in Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, David de Mormaer, was 26 and her mother, Matilda of Huntington, was 21. She married Alan John Armstrong from 1196 to 1200, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1228, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1173–1228":"1173–1228","1164–1255":"1164–1255","1196–1271":"1196–1271","–Male":"Surnud","1148–Male":"1148–Surnud","1152–1181":"1152–1181","1228":"1228","1148":"1148","1255":"1255","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1271":"1271","1181":"1181","1196 to 1200":"1196 kuni 1200","Scotland":"Scotland","Scone, Perthshire, Scotland":"Scone, Perthshire, Scotland","Falde,Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1173–1228":"1173–1228","1164–1255":"1164–1255","1196–1271":"1196–1271","–Male":"Kuollut","1148–Male":"1148–Kuollut","1152–1181":"1152–1181","1228":"1228","1148":"1148","1255":"1255","1164":"1164","1196":"1196","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1271":"1271","1181":"1181","1196 to 1200":"vuodesta 1196 vuoteen 1200","Scotland":"Scotland","Scone, Perthshire, Scotland":"Scone, Perthshire, Scotland","Falde,Dumfriesshire, Scotland.":"Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"